This problem only happen in the first run of a run task using API in automation test team's source code. It is not reproducible using BIRT All in one.
We should firstly try to reproduce the problem using our own java code. That is, execute a run task using API calls.
*** Bug 212978 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***

It's caused by Eclipse OSGi implementation used in BIRT2.2. In that OSGi implementation, OSGi registers a URLStreamHandlerFactory to java.net.URL. That URLStreamHandlerFactory creates URLStreamHandler which will also want to read its target jar's dependent jar(s)(Specified as Class-Path field in taget jar's MANIFEST.MF) when a URLClassLoader scans all its registered URLs to find a class.
In the environment that bug occurs, There is a jtds-1.2.jar in the JDBC Driver dir, The "Class-Path" field in its MANIFEST.MF is "jcifs.jar". But there is no jcifs.jar in the same dir. So, A runtime exception is threw from openConnection(URL url) method in org.eclipse.osgi.framework.internal.protocol.MultiplexingURLStreamHandler while loading specified JDBC Driver.
4 ways to avoid this problem: 1. upgrade to use BIRT2.3 2. copy a jcifs.jar to the JDBC driver dir in all deployed BIRT2.2 webapps 3. remove the "Class-Path" field from the MANIFEST.MF in jtds-1.2.jar 4. Copy OSGi implementation jars used in BIRT2.3 to BIRT2.2's \\platform\plugins dir.
Another way to avoid this problem: just remove jtds-1.2.jar in the JDBC driver dir if MS SQL Server is not one of the backward dbs.
